# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: exit-sign
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Accessibility can be viewed as the "ability to access" and benefit from some system or entity.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] The concept focuses on enabling access for people with disabilities, or enabling access through the use of assistive technology; however, research and development in accessibility brings benefits to everyone.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Therefore, an accessible society should eliminate digital divide or knowledge divide.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Accessibility is not to be confused with usability, which is the extent to which a product (such as a device, service, or environment) can be used by specified users to achieve specified goals with effectiveness, efficiency, and satisfaction in a specified context of use.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Accessibility is also strongly related to universal design, the process of creating products that are usable by the widest possible range of people, operating within the widest possible range of situations.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Universal design typically provides a single general solution that can accommodate people with disabilities as well as the rest of the population.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] By contrast, accessible design is focused on ensuring that there are no barriers to accessibility for all people, including those with disabilities.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] The disability rights movement advocates equal access to social, political, and economic life which includes not only physical access but access to the same tools, services, organizations and facilities as non-disabled people (e.g., museums).
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Article 9 of the United Nations Convention on the Rights of Persons with Disabilities commits signatories to provide for full accessibility in their countries.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] While it is often used to describe facilities or amenities to assist people with impaired mobility, through the provision of facilities like wheelchair ramps, the term can include other types of disability.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Accessible facilities therefore extend to areas such as Braille signage, elevators, audio signals at pedestrian crossings, walkway contours, website accessibility and accessible publishing.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Government mandates, such as the Section 508 Amendment to the Rehabilitation Act of 1973, Web Content Accessibility Guidelines (WCAG), and the Disability Discrimination Act 1995 (DDA) enforce practices to standardize accessibility testing engineering in product development.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Accessibility modifications may be required to enable persons with disabilities to gain access to education, employment, transportation, housing, recreation, or even simply to exercise their right to vote.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Legislation may also be enacted on a state, provincial or local level.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] In Ontario, Canada, the Ontarians with Disabilities Act of 2001 is meant to "improve the identification, removal and prevention of barriers faced by persons with disabilities".
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] The European Union (EU), which has signed the United Nations' Convention on the Rights of Persons with Disabilities, also has adopted a European Disability Strategy for 2010–20.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] A *European Accessibility Act* was proposed in late 2012.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] This Act would establish standards within member countries for accessible products, services, and public buildings.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] The harmonization of accessibility standards within the EU "would facilitate the social integration of persons with disabilities and the elderly and their mobility across member states, thereby also fostering the free movement principle".
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Assistive technology is the creation of a new device that assists a person in completing a task that would otherwise be impossible.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Some examples include new computer software programs like screen readers, and inventions such as assistive listening devices, including hearing aids, and traffic lights with a standard color code that enables colorblind individuals to understand the correct signal.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Adaptive technology is the modification, or adaptation, of existing devices, methods, or the creation of new uses for existing devices, to enable a person to complete a task.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Examples include the use of remote controls, and the autocomplete (word completion) feature in computer word processing programs, which both help individuals with mobility impairments to complete tasks.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Adaptations to wheelchair tires are another example; widening the tires enables wheelchair users to move over soft surfaces, such as deep snow on ski hills, and sandy beaches.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Assistive technology and adaptive technology have a key role in developing the means for people with disabilities to live more independently, and to more fully participate in mainstream society.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Recent research has demonstrated that tablet-based assistive technologies can enable adults with intellectual and motor disabilities to engage in independent leisure activities and video communication, enhancing social participation and autonomy.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] These programs use commercially available tablets and applications with simplified interfaces to support users in accessing media and making video calls with minimal assistance.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] In order to have access to assistive or adaptive technology, however, educating the public and even legislating requirements to incorporate this technology have been necessary.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] The UN CRPD, and courts in the United States, Japan, UK, and elsewhere, have decided that when it is needed to assure secret ballot, authorities should provide voters with assistive technology.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] The European Court of Human Rights, on the contrary, in case Toplak v.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Slovenia ruled that due to high costs, the abandonment of the assistive equipment in elections did not violate human rights.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Accessibility of employment covers a wide range of issues, from skills training, to occupational therapy, finding employment, and retaining employment.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Employment rates for workers with disabilities are lower than for the general workforce.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Workers in Western countries fare relatively well, having access to more services and training as well as legal protections against employment discrimination.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Despite this, in the United States the 2012 unemployment rate for workers with disabilities was 12.9%, while it was 7.3% for workers without disabilities.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] More than half of workers with disabilities (52%) earned less than $25,000 in the previous year, compared with just 38% of workers with no disabilities.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] This translates into an earnings gap where individuals with disabilities earn about 25 percent less of what workers without disabilities earn.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Among occupations with 100,000 or more people, dishwashers had the highest disability rate (14.3%), followed by refuse and recyclable material collectors (12.7%), personal care aides (11.9%), and janitors and building cleaners (11.8%).
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] The rates for refuse and recyclable material collectors, personal care aides, and janitors and building cleaners were not statistically different from one another.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Surveys of non-Western countries are limited, but the available statistics also indicate fewer jobs being filled by workers with disabilities.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] In India, a large 1999 survey found that "of the 'top 100 multinational companies' in the country [...] the employment rate of persons with disabilities in the private sector was a mere 0.28%, 0.05% in multinational companies and only 0.58% in the top 100 IT companies in the country".
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] India, like much of the world, has large sections of the economy that are without strong regulation or social protections, such as the informal economy.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Other factors have been cited as contributing to the high unemployment rate, such as public service regulations.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Expenses related to adaptive or assistive technology required to participate in the workforce may be tax deductible expenses for individuals with a medical practitioner's prescription in some jurisdictions.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Disability management (DM) is a specialized area of human resources that supports efforts of employers to better integrate and retain workers with disabilities.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Some workplaces have policies in place to provide "reasonable accommodation" for employees with disabilities, but many do not.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] In some jurisdictions, employers may have legal requirements to end discrimination against persons with disabilities.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] One of the biggest challenges for employers is in developing policies and practises to manage employees who develop disabilities during the course of employment.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Even where these exist, they tend to focus on workplace injuries, overlooking job retention challenges faced by employees who acquire a non-occupation injury or illness.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Protecting employability is a factor that can help close the unemployment gap for persons with disabilities.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Automobile accessibility also refers to ease of use by disabled people.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Automobiles, whether a car or a van, can be adapted for a range of physical disabilities.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Foot pedals can be raised, or replaced with hand-controlled devices.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Wheelchair hoists, lifts or ramps may be customized according to the needs of the driver.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Ergonomic adaptations, such as a lumbar support cushion, may also be needed.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Generally, the more limiting the disability, the more expensive the adaptation needed for the vehicle.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Financial assistance is available through some organizations, such as Motability in the United Kingdom, which requires a contribution by the prospective vehicle owner.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Motability makes vehicles available for purchase or lease.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] When an employee with a disability requires an adapted car for work use, the employee does not have to pay for a "reasonable adjustment" in the United Kingdom; if the employer is unable to pay the cost, assistance is offered by government programs.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] A significant development in transportation, and public transport in particular, to achieve accessibility, is the move to "low-floor" vehicles.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] In a low-floor vehicle, access to part or all of the passenger cabin is unobstructed from one or more entrances by the presence of steps, enabling easier access for the infirm or people with push chairs.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] A further aspect may be that the entrance and corridors are wide enough to accommodate a wheelchair.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Low-floor vehicles have been developed for buses, trolleybuses, trams and trains.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] A low floor in the vehicular sense is normally combined in a conceptual meaning with normal pedestrian access from a standard kerb (curb) height.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] However, the accessibility of a low-floor vehicle can also be utilised from slightly raising portions of kerb at bus stops, or through use of level boarding bus rapid transit stations or tram stops.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] The combination of access from a kerb was the technological development of the 1990s, as step-free interior layouts for buses had existed in some cases for decades, with entrance steps being introduced as chassis designs and overall height regulations changed.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Low-floor buses may also be designed with special height adjustment controls that permit a stationary bus to temporarily lower itself to ground level, permitting wheelchair access.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] In the United Kingdom, local transport authorities are responsible for checking that all people who live within their area can access essential opportunities and services, and where gaps in provision are identified the local authorities are responsible for organizing changes to make new connections.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] These requirements are defined in the UK Community Planning Acts legislation and more detailed guidance has been issued by the Department for Transport for each local authority.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] This includes the requirement to produce an Accessibility Plan under Community Planning legislation and to incorporate this within their Local Transport Plan.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] An Accessibility Plan sets out how each local authority plans to improve access to employment, learning, health care, food shops and other services of local importance, particularly for disadvantaged groups and areas.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Accessibility targets are defined in the accessibility plans, these are often the distance or time to access services by different modes of transport including walking, cycling and public transport.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Accessibility Planning was introduced as a result of the report "Making the Connections: Final Report on Transport and Social Exclusion".
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] This report was the result of research carried out by the Social Exclusion Unit.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] The United Kingdom also has a "code of practice" for making train and stations accessible: "Accessible Train and Station Design for Disabled People: A Code of Practice".
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] This code of practice was first published in 2002 with the objective of compliance to Section 71B of the Railways Act 1993, and revised after a public consultation period in 2008.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Some transport companies have since improved the accessibility of their services, such as incorporating low-floor buses into their stock as standard.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] The system will utilise clear signage at stations and QR codes, allowing customers to send details of the assistance they require and their planned journey to staff remotely.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Making public services fully accessible to the public has led to some technological innovations.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Public announcement systems using audio induction loop technology can broadcast announcements directly into the hearing aid of anyone with a hearing impairment, making them useful in such public places as auditoriums and train stations.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] The UN Convention on the Rights of Persons with Disabilities (2006) requires 'appropriate measures' to ensure people with disabilities are able to 'access, on an equal basis with others','the physical environment', 'transportation' and 'other facilities and services open or provided to the public'.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] This requirement also applies to 'roads' and 'transportation' as well as 'buildings, and other indoor and outdoor facilities'.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] At the same time, promotion of active travel, or 'shared space' initiatives to pedestrianise city centres can introduce unintended barriers, especially for pedestrians who are visually impaired and who can find these environments confusing or even dangerous.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] It is important to have effective mechanisms to ensure that urban spaces are designed to be inclusive of pedestrians with disabilities.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] These can include early consultation with disabled persons or their representative organisations, and appropriate regulation of city planning.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Most existing and new housing, even in the wealthiest nations, lack basic accessibility features unless the designated, immediate occupant of a home currently has a disability.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] However, there are some initiatives to change typical residential practices so that new homes incorporate basic access features such as zero-step entries and door widths adequate for wheelchairs to pass through.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Occupational Therapists are a professional group skilled in the assessment and making of recommendations to improve access to homes.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] They are involved in both the adaptation of existing housing to improve accessibility, and in the design of future housing.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] The broad concept of Universal design is relevant to housing, as it is to all aspects of the built environment.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Furthermore, a Visitability movement begun by grass roots disability advocates in the 1980s focuses specifically on changing construction practices in new housing.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] This movement, a network of interested people working in their locales, works on educating, passing laws, and spurring voluntary home access initiatives with the intention that basic access become a routine part of new home construction.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Accessibility in the design of housing and household devices has become more prominent in recent decades due to a rapidly ageing population in developed countries.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Ageing seniors may wish to continue living independently, but the ageing process naturally increases the disabilities that a senior citizen will experience.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] A growing trend is the desire for many senior citizens to 'age in place', living as independently as possible for as long as possible.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Accessibility modifications that allow ageing in place are becoming more common.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Housing may even be designed to incorporate accessibility modifications that can be made throughout the life cycle of the residents.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] The English Housing Survey for 2018/19 found only 9% of homes in England have key features, such as a toilet at entrance level and sufficiently wide doorways, to deem them accessible.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] This was an improvement from 5% in 2005.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] More than 400,000 wheelchair users in England were living in homes which are neither adapted nor accessible.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Under the Convention on the Rights of Persons with Disabilities, states parties are bound to assure accessible elections, voting, and voting procedures.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] In 2018, the United Nations Committee on the Rights of Persons with Disabilities issued an opinion that all polling stations should be fully accessible.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] At the European Court of Human Rights, there are currently two ongoing cases about the accessibility of polling places and voting procedures.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] They were brought against Slovenia by two voters and the Slovenian Disability Rights Association.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] As of January 2020, the case, called Toplak and Mrak v.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] The aim of the court procedure is to make accessible all polling places in Europe.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Advances in information technology and telecommunications have represented a leap forward for accessibility.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Access to the technology is restricted to those who can afford it, but it has become more widespread in Western countries in recent years.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] For those who use it, it provides the ability to access information and services by minimizing the barriers of distance and cost as well as the accessibility and usability of the interface.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] In many countries this has led to initiatives, laws and/or regulations that aim toward providing universal access to the internet and to phone systems at reasonable cost to citizens.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] A major advantage of advanced technology is its flexibility.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Some technologies can be used at home, in the workplace, and in school, expanding the ability of the user to participate in various spheres of daily life.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Augmentative and alternative communication technology is one such area of IT progress.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] It includes inventions such as speech-generating devices, teletypewriter devices, adaptive pointing devices to replace computer mouse devices, and many others.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Mobile telecommunications devices and computer applications are also equipped with accessibility features.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] They can be adapted to create accessibility to a range of tasks, and may be suitable for different kinds of disability.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Each kind of disability requires a different kind of accommodation, and this may require analysis by a medical specialist, an educational specialist or a job analysis when the impairment requires accommodation.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] One of the first areas where information technology improved the quality of life for disabled individuals is the voice operated wheelchair.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Quadriplegics have the most profound disability, and the voice operated wheelchair technology was first developed in 1977 to provide increased mobility.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] The original version replaced the joystick system with a module that recognized 8 commands.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Many other technology accommodation improvements have evolved from this initial development.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Missing arms or fingers may make the use of a keyboard and mouse difficult or impossible.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Technological improvements such as speech recognition devices and software can improve access.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] A communication disorder interferes with the ability to produce clearly understandable speech.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] There can be many different causes, such as nerve degeneration, muscle degeneration, stroke, and vocal cord injury.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] The modern method to deal with speaking disabilities has been to provide a text interface for a speech synthesizer for complete vocal disability.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] This can be a great improvement for people that have been limited to the use of a throat vibrator to produce speech since the 1960s.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] An individual satisfies the definition of hearing disabled when hearing loss is about 30 dB for a single frequency, but this is not always perceptible as a disability.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] For example, loss of sensitivity in one ear interferes with sound localization (directional hearing), which can interfere with communication in a crowd.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] This is often recognized when certain words are confused during normal conversation.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] This can interfere with voice-only interfaces, like automated customer service telephone systems, because it is sometimes difficult to increase the volume and repeat the message.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Mild to moderate hearing loss may be accommodated with a hearing aid that amplifies ambient sounds.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Portable devices with speed recognition that can produce text can reduce problems associated with understanding conversation.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] This kind of hearing loss is relatively common, and this often grows worse with age.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] The modern method to deal with profound hearing disability is the Internet using email or word processing applications.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] The telecommunications device for the deaf (TDD) became available in the form of the teletype (TTY) during the 1960s.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] These devices consist of a keyboard, display and modem that connects two or more of these devices using a dedicated wire or plain old telephone service.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Modern computer animation allows for sign language avatars to be integrated into public areas.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] This technology could potentially make train station announcements, news broadcasts, etc. accessible when a human interpreter is not available.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Sign language can also be incorporated into film; for example, all movies shown in Brazilian movie theaters must have a Brazilian Sign Language video track available to play alongside the film via a second screen.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] A wide array of technology products is available to assist with visual impairment.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] These include screen magnification for monitors, screen-reading software for computers and mobile devices, mouse-over speech synthesis for browsing, braille displays, braille printers, braille cameras, and voice-activated phones and tablets.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] One emerging product that will make ordinary computer displays available for the blind is the refreshable tactile display, which is very different from a conventional braille display.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] This provides a raised surface corresponding to the bright and dim spots on a conventional display.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] An example is the Touch Sight Camera for the Blind.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Speech Synthesis Markup Language and Speech Recognition Grammar Specification) are relatively recent technologies intended to standardize communication interfaces using Augmented BNF Form and XML Form.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] These technologies assist visual impairments and physical impairment by providing interactive access to web content without the need to visually observe the content.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] While these technologies provides access for visually impaired individuals, the primary benefactor has been automated systems that replace live human customer service representatives that handle telephone calls.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Most of the supporting work for design for cognitive accessibility is for adapted systems, a subset of assistive technology.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Problem framing: One of the most daunting problems with any sort of project involving access by cognitively disabled persons is understanding the end users.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Also, in many instances, systems for this group of end-users also involve a secondary group of caregivers.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Both groups need to have their needs and wants carefully considered.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Standards There are several frameworks and standards to guide developers for adapted systems.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Most notable are the ISO group and Resna.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Examples of these standards: RESNA - ANSI/RESNA CA-1:2016 ISO - ISO-TC173-WG10_N238_ISO 21801-1 2020 As well as parts of the World Wide Web Consortium's WAI-IG, and WebAIM's Cognitive accessibility design considerations.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Microsoft and other design frameworks and tools have also published sets of guidelines.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] There have been a few major movements to coordinate a set of guidelines for accessibility for the web.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] The first and most well known is The Web Accessibility Initiative (WAI), which is part of the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C).
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] This organization developed the Web Content Accessibility Guidelines (WCAG) 1.0 and 2.0 which explain how to make Web content accessible to everyone, including people with disabilities.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Web "content" generally refers to the information in a Web page or Web application, including text, images, forms, and sounds.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] The WCAG is separated into three levels of compliance, A, AA and AAA.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Each level requires a stricter set of conformance guidelines, such as different versions of HTML (Transitional vs Strict) and other techniques that need to be incorporated into coding before accomplishing validation.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Online tools allow users to submit their website and automatically run it through the WCAG guidelines and produce a report, stating whether or not they conform to each level of compliance.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Adobe Dreamweaver also offers plugins which allow web developers to test these guidelines on their work from within the program.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Another source of web accessibility guidance comes from the US government.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] In response to Section 508 of the US Rehabilitation Act, the Access Board developed standards to which U.S. federal agencies must comply in order to make their sites accessible.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] General Services Administration has developed a website where one can take online training courses for free to learn about these rules.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] While WCAG provides much technical information for use by web designers, coders and editors, *BS 8878:2010 Web accessibility – Code of Practice* has been introduced, initially in the UK, to help site owners and product managers to understand the importance of accessibility.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] It includes advice on the business case behind accessibility, and how organisations might usefully update their policies and production processes to embed accessibility in their business-as-usual.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] On 28 May 2019, BS 8878 was superseded by *ISO 30071-1*, the international Standard that built on BS 8878 and expanded it for international use.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Another useful idea is for websites to include a web accessibility statement on the site.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] While validations against WCAG, and other accessibility badges can also be included, they should be put lower down the statement, as most disabled people still do not understand these technical terms.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Equal access to education for students with disabilities is supported in some countries by legislation.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] It is still challenging for some students with disabilities to fully participate in mainstream education settings, but many adaptive technologies and assistive programs are making improvements.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] In India, the Medical Council of India has now passed the directives to all the medical institutions to make them accessible to persons with disabilities.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] This happened due to a petition by Satendra Singh founder of Infinite Ability.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Students with a physical or mental impairment or learning disability may require note-taking assistance, which may be provided by a business offering such services, as with tutoring services.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Talking books in the form of talking textbooks are available in Canadian secondary and post-secondary schools.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Also, students may require adaptive technology to access computers and the Internet.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] These may be tax-exempt expenses in some jurisdictions with a medical prescription.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] It is important to ensure that the accessibility in education includes assessments.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Accessibility in testing or assessments entails the extent to which a test and its constituent item set eliminates barriers and permits the test-taker to demonstrate their knowledge of the tested content.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] With the passage of the No Child Left Behind Act of 2001 in the United States, student accountability in essential content areas such as reading, mathematics, and science has become a major area of focus in educational reform.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] As a result, test developers have needed to create tests to ensure all students, including those with special needs (e.g., students identified with disabilities), are given the opportunity to demonstrate the extent to which they have mastered the content measured on state assessments.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Currently, states are permitted to develop two different types of tests in addition to the standard grade-level assessments to target students with special needs.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] First, the alternate assessment may be used to report proficiency for up to 1% of students in a state.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Second, new regulations permit the use of alternate assessments based on modified academic achievement standards to report proficiency for up to 2% of students in a state.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] To ensure that these new tests generate results that allow valid inferences to be made about student performance, they must be accessible to as many people as possible.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] The Test Accessibility and Modification Inventory (TAMI) and its companion evaluation tool, the Accessibility Rating Matrix (ARM), were designed to facilitate the evaluation of tests and test items with a focus on enhancing their accessibility.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Both instruments incorporate the principles of accessibility theory and were guided by research on universal design, assessment accessibility, cognitive load theory, and research on item writing and test development.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] The TAMI is a non-commercial instrument that has been made available to all state assessment directors and testing companies.
[src:exit-sign/accessibility] Assessment researchers have used the ARM to conduct accessibility reviews of state assessment items for several state departments of education.
[src:exit-sign/active-fire-protection] Manual fire suppression includes the use of a fire blanket, fire extinguisher, or a standpipe system.
[src:exit-sign/active-fire-protection] A fire blanket is a sheet of fire retardant material that is designed to be placed over a fire to smother it out.
[src:exit-sign/active-fire-protection] Small fire blankets are meant for inception stage fires.
[src:exit-sign/active-fire-protection] They are normally made of fiberglass or Kevlar.
[src:exit-sign/active-fire-protection] Larger ones can be found in laboratories and factories, and are designed to be wrapped around a person whose clothes have caught fire.
[src:exit-sign/active-fire-protection] Fire extinguishers are devices that contain and discharge a substance that extinguishes or puts out a fire.
[src:exit-sign/active-fire-protection] These handheld devices come in a huge range of sizes, but the most common are portable fire extinguishers, typically weighing up to 15 kg in total.
[src:exit-sign/active-fire-protection] These can be easily handled and operated by one person and placement can either be wall-mounted, on a fire extinguisher trolley or housed inside a cabinet.
[src:exit-sign/active-fire-protection] Fire extinguishers are one of the most common manual fire suppression devices and are required in all commercial buildings and vehicles.
[src:exit-sign/active-fire-protection] Fire extinguishers can be used with little to no training and are meant for small incipient stage fires.
[src:exit-sign/active-fire-protection] The most common extinguisher is the ABC extinguisher and are found in most offices and homes.
[src:exit-sign/active-fire-protection] It can be used on normal fires, liquid fires, and electrical fires.
[src:exit-sign/active-fire-protection] There are also special extinguishers for kitchen fires and for use on burning metals, those being Class K and Class D respectively.
[src:exit-sign/active-fire-protection] Standpipes are installed in most large, multistory buildings.
[src:exit-sign/active-fire-protection] There are two types of standpipes: dry and wet.
[src:exit-sign/active-fire-protection] Most standpipes are dry systems and cannot be used by the public.
[src:exit-sign/active-fire-protection] Dry systems require a fire engine to pump water into the system.
[src:exit-sign/active-fire-protection] Most dry systems do not have pre-connected hoses and require firefighters to bring in the hose.
[src:exit-sign/active-fire-protection] In wet systems, there is always water in the pipes and they can be used by anyone.
[src:exit-sign/active-fire-protection] Wet systems will have hoses so building occupants can try and extinguish fires.
[src:exit-sign/active-fire-protection] Wet systems are becoming less common with the increase in number of sprinkler systems being installed.
[src:exit-sign/active-fire-protection] In some systems, firefighters have the option of pumping a Fire Department Connection (FDC) which will increase the water pressure at a standpipe in the event of a fire pump failure or loss of pressure.
[src:exit-sign/active-fire-protection] Typically, these systems pressurize the sprinkler system or the standpipe but not both at the same time.
[src:exit-sign/active-fire-protection] Automatic control means are any form of suppression that requires no human intervention these can include a fire sprinkler system, a gaseous clean agent, or automatic foam suppression system.
[src:exit-sign/active-fire-protection] Most automatic suppression systems would be found in large commercial kitchens or other high-risk areas.
[src:exit-sign/active-fire-protection] Fire sprinkler systems are installed in all types of buildings, commercial and residential.
[src:exit-sign/active-fire-protection] They are usually located at ceiling level and are connected to a reliable water source, most commonly municipal water supply.
[src:exit-sign/active-fire-protection] A typical automatic sprinkler system operates when heat at the site of a fire causes a fusible link or glass component in the sprinkler head to fail, thereby releasing the water from the sprinkler head.
[src:exit-sign/active-fire-protection] This means that only the sprinkler heads at the fire location actuate – not all the sprinklers on a floor or in a building.
[src:exit-sign/active-fire-protection] However, certain systems, such as deluge systems, do spray water from all heads in the same zone upon actuation.
[src:exit-sign/active-fire-protection] Sprinkler systems help to reduce the growth of a fire, thereby increasing life safety and limiting structural damage.
[src:exit-sign/active-fire-protection] Gaseous clean agents are installed to result in less fire and water damage than sprinklers, such as in computer rooms.
[src:exit-sign/active-fire-protection] The system works by flooding an area with a gas which interferes with the fire tetrahedron.
[src:exit-sign/active-fire-protection] These systems are often found in areas where people are not going to be present when the system is activated such as datacenters, cooling systems, and other industrial applications.
[src:exit-sign/active-fire-protection] Activating a gaseous clean agent system when people are present can cause injury or death, and are usually equipped with an audible notification system to warn any potential occupants to evacuate the area.
[src:exit-sign/active-fire-protection] Automatic foam suppression systems come in three main forms low expansion, medium expansion, and high expansion.
[src:exit-sign/active-fire-protection] Low expansion foam expands less than 20 times its original size.
[src:exit-sign/active-fire-protection] These systems can be installed in a variety of places but are commonly found in places where hydrocarbons are stored.
[src:exit-sign/active-fire-protection] Low expansion foam systems when using film forming work by making a blanket of foam over the burning liquid to both cool it down and suppress the vapors.
[src:exit-sign/active-fire-protection] Medium expansion foam expands between 20 and 200 times its original size.
[src:exit-sign/active-fire-protection] These can be installed in outdoor settings like transfer stations or for use in open pits.
[src:exit-sign/active-fire-protection] Medium foam is used outdoors because it is denser than high expansion and will not blow away as easily.
[src:exit-sign/active-fire-protection] It works by covering what is on fire in a thick blanket of foam to smother it and suppress vapors.
[src:exit-sign/active-fire-protection] High expansion foam expands between 200 and 1000 times its original size.
[src:exit-sign/active-fire-protection] These systems are commonly installed in large volume areas like airplane hangars, mine shafts, and ship holds.
[src:exit-sign/active-fire-protection] These systems are normally installed inside and make a very light foam.
[src:exit-sign/active-fire-protection] They extinguish the fire by rapid smothering and cooling.
[src:exit-sign/active-fire-protection] Its rapid rate of expansion enables it to fill large areas with foam rapidly.
[src:exit-sign/active-fire-protection] When used on LNG tanks they provide an added insulation layer that helps reduce the vapor rate.
[src:exit-sign/active-fire-protection] Nozzles that are powered by electrical energy that is generated and supplied by fire detection and control devices and are typically closed.
[src:exit-sign/active-fire-protection] ILDFA uses a dual approach, combining a water-based fire suppression system in conjunction with a hollow, perforated flooring system to drain and remove spilled flammable liquid.
[src:exit-sign/active-fire-protection] This approach reduces the risk of pool fires inside infrastructure by diverting any leaked fuel away from potential ignition sources or by extinguishing any flammable liquid fire by depriving it of oxygen once it is removed.
[src:exit-sign/active-fire-protection] Fire detection works using smoke or heat sensors.
[src:exit-sign/active-fire-protection] These systems are very effective tool at alerting people in the immediate vicinity of where the fire is detected but building regulations require an integrated fire detection system.
[src:exit-sign/active-fire-protection] These system not only alerts people throughout the building by triggering the fire alarm but it can also summon emergency services.
[src:exit-sign/active-fire-protection] There are two types of systems available – addressable and conventional.
[src:exit-sign/active-fire-protection] Addressable systems monitor the specific location of each device (e.g. smoke detector, call point or sounder).
[src:exit-sign/active-fire-protection] It means in the event of a fire or other emergency you know exactly where the problem is.
[src:exit-sign/active-fire-protection] This saves precious time and helps the emergency services prevent the loss of life and serious damage.
[src:exit-sign/active-fire-protection] Conventional systems can only determine the problem is in a general area and thus are more suited for small sites.
[src:exit-sign/active-fire-protection] When the fire detection system is activated it can also send an alert to the local fire department, broadcast a prerecorded warning message and unlock the buildings access control system.
[src:exit-sign/active-fire-protection] Hypoxic air fire prevention systems, also known as oxygen reduction systems are new automatic fire prevention systems that permanently reduce the oxygen concentration inside the protected volumes so that ignition or fire spreading cannot occur.
[src:exit-sign/active-fire-protection] Unlike traditional fire suppression systems that usually extinguish fire after it is detected, hypoxic air is able to prevent fires.
[src:exit-sign/active-fire-protection] At lower altitudes hypoxic air is safe to breathe for healthy individuals.
[src:exit-sign/active-fire-protection] All AFP systems are required to be installed and maintained in accordance with strict guidelines in order to maintain compliance with the local building code and the fire code.
[src:exit-sign/active-fire-protection] AFP works alongside modern architectural designs and construction materials and fire safety education to prevent, retard, and suppress structural fires.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] Airbus originated from **Airbus Industrie GIE**, a consortium of European aerospace companies established in 1970 to produce a wide-body aircraft to compete with American-built airliners.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] In 2000, the consortium's parent firms—Aérospatiale-Matra of France, DASA of Germany, and CASA of Spain—merged to form the **European Aeronautic Defence and Space Company** (**EADS**), which later acquired full ownership of Airbus Industrie.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] Reflecting its multinational origins, the company operates offices and assembly plants in France, Germany, Spain, and the United Kingdom, along with more recent additions in Canada, Malaysia, the United States, Morocco, and India.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] Airbus's headquarters are legally registered in Leiden, Netherlands, while day-to-day management is conducted from the company's main office in Blagnac, France.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] The *SE* in its name denotes *Societas Europaea*, a public company under European Union corporate law.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] Airbus is led by CEO Guillaume Faury and is included in the EURO STOXX 50 stock market index.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] Since its inception in 2000, the company's shares have been listed on the Paris, Frankfurt, and four Spanish stock exchanges, including the Bolsa de Madrid.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] The company traces its origins to the formation of the *Airbus Industrie GIE*, a consortium of European aerospace companies established in 1970 to produce a wide-body aircraft to compete with American-built airliners.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] France's state-owned Aérospatiale owned 37.9% of Airbus Industrie, West Germany's Deutsche Airbus also owned 37.9%, British Aerospace held 20%, and Spain's largely state-owned CASA owned 4.2%.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] In 2000, the European Aeronautic Defence and Space Company (EADS) was established through the merger of Aérospatiale and Matra of France, DASA (the successor to Deutsche Airbus) of Germany, and CASA.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] EADS held 100% of *Eurocopter* *S.A.*, established in 1992 and later renamed Airbus Helicopters, along with 80% of Airbus Industrie GIE, which was quickly reorganised as *Airbus S.A.S.*, a simplified joint-stock company.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] In 2006, EADS acquired the remaining 20% of Airbus S.A.S. from BAE Systems (the successor of British Aerospace).
[src:exit-sign/airbus] EADS was renamed *Airbus Group N.V.* in 2014 and *Airbus Group S.E.* in 2015.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] Airbus S.A.S. and Airbus Group S.E. were merged in January 2017, and in April 2017 the combined entity adopted the name Airbus SE.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] Since then, Airbus SE has owned the commercial aircraft manufacturing operations while also serving as the parent company of the other two divisions, Airbus Defence and Space and Airbus Helicopters.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] The Airbus product line started with the A300 in 1972, the world's first wide-body, twinjet aircraft.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] Initial sales were slow, leading to calls to end the Airbus program.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] However, the aircraft would greatly benefit from the 1976 introduction of the ETOPS 90 rule, which allowed twinjet aircraft to operate up to 90 minutes—an increase from 60 minutes—away from the nearest airport.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] Under the new rule, the A300 was able to operate over the North Atlantic, the Bay of Bengal, and the Indian Ocean, making it a more efficient alternative to the trijets and four-engined aircraft offered by competitors, leading to renewed airline interest and a sharp increase in sales.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] Airbus then developed the A310 to meet demand for a shorter-body but longer-range version of the A300.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] The aircraft also introduced a glass cockpit, which eliminated the need for a flight engineer, and a redesigned rear fuselage that used space more efficiently, creating additional capacity.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] The A310 was manufactured from 1981 to 1998.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] These design changes were later incorporated into the A300, resulting in the A300-600.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] Building on its success with the A300, Airbus developed the narrow-body A320 aircraft that was launched in 1987, which became and remains a major commercial success.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] The A320 was the first commercial jet to use a digital fly-by-wire control system.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] All Airbus models developed since have adopted cockpit systems similar to the A320, making it easier for crews to transition between aircraft types.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] The success of the A320 led Airbus to introduce a lengthened version, the A321, in 1993, followed by the shorter A319 in 1995 and the even shorter A318 in 2002.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] In 2016, Airbus re-engineered the narrow-body family under a programme called the A320neo (*new engine option*).
[src:exit-sign/airbus] Airbus also embarked on an effort to develop new wide-body aircraft derived from the cross-section of the A300, but with greater range and seating capacity and integrating technologies developed from the A320 programme.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] This effort led to the introduction of the four-engine A340 in 1991 and the twinjet A330 in 1992.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] At that time, Airbus wanted to offer a four-engined jet aircraft to allow for transpacific flights.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] However, during the aircraft's development, new ETOPS rules extended twinjet operations to 120 minutes in 1986 and 180 minutes in 1989.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] Although these changes hurt sales of the A340, they greatly benefited the A330.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] Production of the A340 ended in 2011, while the A330 was re-engineered as the A330neo (*new engine option*) in 2018.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] In 2005, Airbus introduced the world's largest passenger airliner: the A380 is a four-engine aircraft with two full-length passenger seating decks.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] Intended to challenge the dominance of the Boeing 747 in the long-haul market, the A380 was ultimately a money-losing venture for Airbus due to large development costs and limited sales arising from high operating costs, and production ended in December 2021.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] The A350, a wide-body, twinjet aircraft, was introduced in 2015.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] The A350 was the first Airbus aircraft that was largely produced from carbon-fiber-reinforced polymers.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] It is longer and wider than the fuselage used on the A300, A310, A330, and A340.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] A second narrow-body jet was added to the product list in 2018 when Airbus gained control of the Bombardier CSeries programme, and rebranded it as the A220.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] The jet offers five-abreast seating compared to the six-abreast seating on the A320.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] In December 2024, it was reported that the total aircraft delivery in the year for Airbus has reached 643 units, with 84 planes delivered in November 2024 alone.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] Subsequently, in January 2025, it was reported that Airbus had successfully delivered 766 aircraft to its customers out of 878 orders in the entire 2024, marking a 4% increase from the previous year.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] In October 2025, the A320 overtook the Boeing 737 as the most delivered airliner.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] Airbus Corporate Jets markets and modifies new aircraft for private and corporate customers.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] It has a model range that parallels the commercial aircraft offered by the company.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] Following the entry of the 737-based Boeing Business Jet, Airbus joined the business jet market with the A319 Corporate Jet in 1997.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] Although the term Airbus Corporate Jet was initially used only for the A319CJ, it is now often used for all models, including VIP widebodies.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] As of December 2008, 121 corporate and private jets are operating, and 164 aircraft have been ordered.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] The company also owns 10% of Dassault Aviation, which builds the Falcon family of smaller business jets.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] Airbus Defence and Space markets and either builds or modifies new aircraft for military use.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] Airbus became increasingly interested in developing and selling to the military aviation market in the late 1990s.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] It embarked on two main fields of development: aerial refuelling with the Airbus A310 MRTT (Multi-Role Tanker Transport) and later the Airbus A330 MRTT, and tactical airlift with the Airbus A400M Atlas.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] The company has also continued to market and assemble some military aircraft previously offered by the companies that formed Airbus, notably CASA.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] The A310 and A330-based MRTT aircraft are conversions of civilian airliners.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] The aircraft are called multi-role tanker transports because, in addition to their aerial refuelling capability, the aircraft can also be configured for troop transport, medevac, and cargo transportation.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] The A400M Atlas is a four-engine, turboprop-powered tactical transport aircraft.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] The A400M is sized between the American-made C-130 and the C-17 transports, and while it can carry heavier loads than the C-130, its turboprop engines allow it to retain the ability to use rough landing strips.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] The A400M was developed for European NATO members Belgium, France, Germany, Luxembourg, Spain, Turkey, and the UK, as an alternative to relying on foreign aircraft.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] During development, the A400M programme faced delays and cost overruns; with customer nations stepping in to offer additional subsidies.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] The first aircraft was delivered to the French Air Force in 2013, and by 2023, more than 100 aircraft had been built.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] The Defence and Space division also markets and assembles the EADS CASA C295, a smaller tactical transport aircraft, that was designed and initially manufactured by the Spanish aerospace company CASA.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] Airbus Helicopters builds and markets new rotorcraft for civilian and military use.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] The division was founded formed in 1992 as the Eurocopter Group, through the merger of the helicopter divisions of Aérospatiale and DASA (two of the founding companies of Airbus).
[src:exit-sign/airbus] Airbus Helicopters is the foremost player in the turbine helicopter industry in terms of both revenue and deliveries.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] The division's civilian products include the single-engine H125 and H130, the light twin-engine H135 and H145, the medium twin-engine H155 and H160, the super medium twin-engine H175, and the heavy twin-engine H215 and H225.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] Military products include the Tiger attack helicopter, along with militarised versions of the H125, H135, H145, H160, H175, H215, and H225.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] The company owns 62.5% of NHIndustries joint venture, which builds the NH90 military utility helicopter.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] Commercial aircraft generated 74% of total revenue for the Airbus group in 2018 and 72% in 2023.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] This line of business was the first one in the world to begin field tests with TETRA Enhanced Data Service (TEDS).
[src:exit-sign/airbus] The Airbus Military division, which manufactured tanker, transport, and mission aircraft; Airbus Helicopters, the world's largest helicopter supplier; Astrium, provided systems for aerial, land, naval, and civilian security applications, including Ariane, Galileo, and Cassidian.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] Through Cassidian, EADS was a partner in the Eurofighter consortium as well as in the MBDA missile systems manufacturer.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] Airbus Helicopters, formerly known as Eurocopter, is a helicopter manufacturing and support company.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] Airbus has several final assembly lines for different models and markets.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] Airbus, however, has a number of other plants in different European locations, reflecting its foundation as a consortium.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] For aircraft assembled in Europe, aircraft parts often move between the different factories and the assembly lines via the use of the Beluga and BelugaXL, a fleet modified aircraft capable of carrying entire sections of fuselage.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] For aircraft assembled in China and the United States, the parts needed to build an aircraft meet in a single European location where they are loaded onto ships for the final journey to the assembly line.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] Airbus opened an assembly plant for the A320 family of aircraft in Tianjin, China in 2009.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] Airbus started constructing a $350 million component manufacturing plant in Harbin, China in July 2009.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] It was fully operational by early 2011, the 30,000 square metre plant manufactures composite parts and assembles composite work-packages for the A350 XWB, A320 families and future Airbus programmes.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] Harbin Aircraft Industry Group Corporation, Hafei Aviation Industry Company Ltd, AviChina Industry & Technology and other Chinese partners hold an 80% stake in the plant while Airbus controls the remaining 20%.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] In 2022, the Tianjin plant finished upgrading works to allow for production of A321.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] In 2023, the Tianjin final assembly plant started construction to be expanded with a second production line.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] North America plays a crucial role for Airbus, both in terms of aircraft sales and suppliers.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] Of the approximately 5,300 Airbus jetliners sold worldwide, 2,000 are ordered by North American customers.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] These orders span Airbus' entire product line, from the compact A318 to the massive A380, accommodating 107 to 565 passengers.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] Notably, US contractors contribute significantly, supporting around 120,000 jobs and generating an estimated $5.5 billion in business.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] For instance, one variant of the A380 boasts 51% American content in terms of work share value.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] Plans for a Mobile, Alabama aircraft assembly plant were unveiled by Airbus CEO Fabrice Brégier from the Mobile Convention Centre on 2 July 2012.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] The plans include a $600 million factory at the Mobile Aeroplex at Brookley for the assembly of the A220, A319, A320 and A321 aircraft.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] It could employ up to 1,000 full-time workers when operational.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] Construction began on 8 April 2013, and became operable by 2015, producing up to 50 aircraft per year by 2017.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] On 16 December 2024, it was reported that Airbus had leased 650,000 sq ft of office space in Bengaluru's Whitefield to build its Global Capacity Centre.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] The lease is for 10 years and valued at Rs 500 crore, securing the entire building in Titanium Tech Park.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] In this way, Airbus intends to strengthen its position in India.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] In October 2005 the British Ministry of Defence warned European politicians to stop, as it saw it, interfering in the corporate governance of EADS.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] The former UK Defence Procurement Minister Lord Drayson hinted that the UK government, a major customer for EADS, may withhold future contracts.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] On 4 April 2006, DaimlerChrysler announced its intention to reduce its shareholding from 30% to 22.5%.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] The company placed a value on the stake at "approximately €2.0 billion." Lagardère was to reduce its holding by an identical amount.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] However, Caisse des Dépôts et Consignations, a unit of the French government, acquired 2.25% of EADS.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] At issue, as a result, is the fact that the German and French shareholdings were now in imbalance.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] On 30 August 2006, shortly after the stock price decline caused by the A380 delivery delays, more than 5% of EADS stock was reportedly purchased by the Russian state-owned Vneshtorgbank, bringing its share to nearly 6%.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] In December 2007, Vneshtorgbank sold EADS shares to another state-controlled bank, Vnesheconombank.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] EADS shares were to be delivered by Vneshekonombank to the charter capital of JSC United Aircraft Corporation in 2008.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] On 3 October 2006, shortly after EADS admitted further delays in the Airbus 380 programme would cost the company 4.8 billion euros in lost earnings in 2010, EADS shares, traded on the Paris arm of Euronext, were suspended after they surpassed the 10% loss limit.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] Trading resumed later in the day with the one-day loss holding at 7%.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] In 2007, Dubai Holding acquired 3.12% of EADS stock, making the Dubai buy-out fund one of the largest institutional shareholders.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] In 2008, EADS had arms sales equivalent to $17.9 billion, which constituted 28% of total revenue.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] In April 2013, Daimler sold its shares in EADS.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] As of 31 December 2024, 73.7% of Airbus Group stock is publicly traded on six European stock exchanges (Euronext Paris in France, the Frankfurt Stock Exchange in Germany, and the four regional stock exchanges Bolsa de Madrid, Borsa de Barcelona, Bolsa de Valencia and Bolsa de Bilbao in Spain).
[src:exit-sign/airbus] 0.6% of the shares are treasury shares owned by Airbus, while the remaining 25.7% are owned by a "Contractual Partnership".
[src:exit-sign/airbus] SOGEPA is owned by the French State, GZBV is majority owned by the German state-owned investment and development bank KfW, and SEPI is a Spanish state holding company.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] In April 2020, Airbus announced that it had cut aircraft production by a third due to the COVID-19 outbreak.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] According to Guillaume Faury, the company was "bleeding cash at an unprecedented speed".
[src:exit-sign/airbus] The recession put its survival at stake and presented the need for deep job cuts throughout all Airbus departments.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] 3,000 workers in France were involved in government-assisted furlough schemes.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] Airbus has committed to "Flightpath 2050", an aviation industry plan to reduce noise, CO2, and NOx emissions.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] Airbus was the first aerospace business to become ISO 14001 certified, in January 2007; this is a broader certification covering the whole organisation, not just the aircraft it produces.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] In association with Honeywell and JetBlue, Airbus has developed an aviation biofuel to reduce pollution and dependence on fossil fuels, claiming that this has the potential to replace up to a third of the world's aviation fuel.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] Algae-based biofuel absorbs carbon dioxide during growth and does not compete with food production.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] This alternative may be commercially available by 2030 but algae and other vegetation-based fuels are in an early stage of development, and fuel-bearing algae have been expensive to develop.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] Airbus offers delivery flights to airlines using a 10% biofuel blend in standard engines.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] The fuel does not cut carbon emissions but is free of sulphur emissions, which demonstrates that the fuel could be used in commercial flights in unmodified engines.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] In September 2020, Airbus unveiled three liquid hydrogen-fueled "ZEROe" concept aircraft that it claims could become the first commercial zero-emission aircraft, entering service by 2035.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] The design includes an aircraft with six eight-bladed removable motors.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] At the Airbus Summit in March 2025, Airbus delivered updates on its development of the ZEROe hydrogen powered aircraft.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] Boeing has continually protested over "launch aid" and other forms of government aid to Airbus, while Airbus has argued that Boeing receives illegal subsidies through military and research contracts and tax breaks.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] In July 2004, former Boeing CEO Harry Stonecipher accused Airbus of abusing a 1992 bilateral EU-US agreement providing for disciplines for large civil aircraft support from governments.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] Airbus is given reimbursable launch investment (RLI), called "launch aid" by the US, from European governments, with the money being paid back with interest plus indefinite royalties, but only if the aircraft is a commercial success.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] Airbus contends that this system is fully compliant with the 1992 agreement and WTO rules.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] The agreement allows up to 33% of the programme cost to be met through government loans, which are to be fully repaid within 17 years with interest and royalties.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] These loans are held at a minimum interest rate equal to the cost of government borrowing plus 0.25%, which would be below market rates available to Airbus without government support.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] Airbus claims that since the signature of the EU-US agreement in 1992, it has repaid European governments more than US$6.7 billion and that this is 40% more than it has received.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] Airbus argues that the military contracts awarded to Boeing, the second largest US defence contractor, are in effect a form of subsidy, such as the controversy surrounding the Boeing KC-767 military contracting arrangements.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] The significant US government support of technology development via NASA also provides significant support to Boeing, as do the large tax breaks offered to Boeing, which some people claim are in violation of the 1992 agreement and WTO rules.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] In its recent products such as the 787, Boeing has also been offered direct financial support from local and state governments.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] In January 2005 the European Union and United States trade representatives, Peter Mandelson and Robert Zoellick respectively, agreed to talks aimed at resolving the increasing tensions.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] These talks were not successful with the dispute becoming more acrimonious rather than approaching a settlement.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] WTO ruled in August 2010 and in May 2011 that Airbus had received improper government subsidies through loans with below market rates from several European countries.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] In a separate ruling in February 2011, WTO found that Boeing had received local and federal aid in violation of WTO rules.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] In 2005 the Government Pension Fund of Norway recommended the exclusion of several companies producing cluster bombs or components.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] EADS and its sister company EADS Finance BV were among them, arguing that EADS manufactures "key components for cluster bombs".
[src:exit-sign/airbus] The criticism was centred around TDA, a joint venture between EADS and Thales S.A.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] TDA produced the mortar ammunition PR Cargo, which can be considered cluster ammunition, however this definition has since been successfully battled by EADS.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] EADS and its subsidiaries are now regarded as fulfilling all the conditions of the Ottawa Treaty.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] According to the new point of view, no product of EADS or its subsidiaries falls into the category of antipersonnel mines as defined by the Ottawa Treaty ("landmines under the Ottawa Treaty").
[src:exit-sign/airbus] In April 2006, the fund declared that the basis for excluding EADS from investments related to the production of cluster munitions is no longer valid, however its shareholding of MBDA means the fund still excludes EADS due to its indirect involvement in nuclear weapons production.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] On 2 June 2006 co-CEO Noël Forgeard and Airbus CEO Gustav Humbert resigned following the controversy caused by the June 2006 announcement that deliveries of the A380 would be delayed by a further six months.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] Forgeard was one of a number of executives including Jean-Paul Gut who exercised stock options in November 2005 and March 2006.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] He and twenty-one other executives are under investigation as to whether they knew about the delays in the Airbus A380 project which caused a 26% fall in EADS shares when publicised.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] The French government's actions were also under investigation; The state-owned bank Caisse des Dépots et Consignations (CDC) bought part of Lagardère's 7.5% stake in EADS in April 2006, allowing that latter to partially escape the June 2006 losses.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] In September 2024, Airbus received negative press attention for its links with Aviation Industry Corporation of China (AVIC), a Chinese company that provides aircraft to the Myanmar junta.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] In a joint report, NGOs Justice for Myanmar and Info Birmanie outlined how the supplied aircraft and weapons were used by the Myanmar military to commit war crimes in the Myanmar civil war.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] The report called on Airbus to use its influence to pressure the Chinese firm to end its arms sales to the Myanmar junta.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] In response to the report, Airbus stated its collaboration focused exclusively on the civil domain, and that its conduct complied with all laws and regulations.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] In June 2025, Justice for Myanmar reported that Airbus had completed its divestment from AviChina, AVIC's publicly listed subsidiary, by 1 April 2025.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] In 2003 Tony Yengeni, former chief whip of South Africa's African National Congress, was convicted of fraud worth around US$5 billion relating to an arms deal with South Africa, in which Airbus (formerly EADS) were major players.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] It was claimed that Airbus had admitted that it had "rendered assistance" to around thirty senior officials, including defence force chief General Siphiwe Nyanda, to obtain luxury vehicles.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] In March 2003, South Africa withdrew all charges of bribery against the former head of EADS South Africa, and in September 2004, the prosecutor's office dismissed the bribery charges against Yengeni.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] In August 2012 the UK's Serious Fraud Office opened a criminal investigation into an EADS subsidiary, GPT Special Project Management Ltd, regarding bribery allegations made by GPT's former programme director, Ian Foxley.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] Foxley alleged that luxury cars were bought for senior Saudis, and that millions of pounds sterling were paid to mysterious Cayman Islands companies, possibly to secure a £2 billion contract to renew the Saudi Arabian National Guard's military telecommunications network.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] Foxley's allegations were supported by two other GPT employees.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] The later agreement between Airbus and the SFO on 31 January 2020 excluded the settlement of this case.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] In July 2016, SFO opened a criminal investigation into "suspicions of fraud, bribes and corruption" after Airbus informed British authorities of a failure to disclose the role played by some intermediaries facilitating the sale of aircraft.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] Airbus was required to provide this information in order to benefit from export credits, which the British, French and German governments had suspended.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] In March 2017, the PNF subsequently opened a preliminary investigation into "suspicions of fraud and corruption in civil aviation activities" in cooperation with the SFO.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] The allegations included that from 2012 onwards Airbus was responsible for recruiting and remunerating intermediaries to influence the award of civil and military contracts.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] Payments worth hundreds of millions of euros in alleged secret commissions were made and numerous sales including in Saudi Arabia, Kazakhstan, Philippines, Indonesia, Austria, China and Mauritius were under suspicion of bribery.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] The investigation focused on the Airbus, Strategy and Marketing Organization (SMO), the department responsible for negotiating sales contracts and which, La Tribune reported as having "a network and an incredible influence around the world".
[src:exit-sign/airbus] Directed successively by Jean-Paul Gut and Marwan Lahoud, the SMO was dissolved in 2016 under the new executive director, Thomas Enders, as part of a "clean hands" operation.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] In 2014, in a case referred to as the Kazakhgate affair, a search at Airbus Helicopters by French authorities found emails confirming that Airbus had agreed in principle to pay €12 million in bribes to the Prime Minister of Kazakhstan to facilitate the sale of helicopters.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] Officers from the Central Anti-Corruption Office (OCLCIFF) then searched the home of Marwan Lahoud on 8 February 2016.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] This revealed that two Turkish intermediaries had claimed payment of commissions due in connection with the sale of 160 aircraft to China valued at US$10 billion.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] A message by Lahoud suggested that the commissions could reach US$250 million.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] The SMO was to conceal these commissions as false invoices for a fictitious Caspian pipeline project.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] In January 2020, French, British and American courts validated three agreements between Airbus and the PNF, the UK SFO, and the US DoJ.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] Airbus recognised the charges and agreed to pay fines of €2.1 billion in France, €984 million in the United Kingdom and €526 million in the United States.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] The penalties were the highest ever issued by the French and British bodies.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] These settlements close the prosecution of Airbus regarding the Kazakhstan case but not allegations of misconduct in Saudi Arabia, China and Turkey, which Airbus denies.
[src:exit-sign/airbus] Airbus managers may still be pursued as private individuals.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] It is an airport of entry in the town of Colonie.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] It was built on the site of the Shaker settlement about 6 miles (9.7 km) north of Albany and stretching north to the hamlet of Verdoy.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] It is also located in close proximity to Interstate 87, State Route 155, and State Route 7.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] The airport is considered Class Charlie Airspace.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] Albany International Airport serves as the major air center for the Capital Region, Northeastern New York, and Western New England.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] In 2025, the airport handled just under 1.6 million departing passengers, breaking the record of 1.56 million in 2004.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] Many airlines serve the airport, with Southwest Airlines having the most presence.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] It holds approximately one-third of the total airline share at Albany.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] Along with Southwest Airlines, Albany sees service with many other low-cost carriers, including JetBlue Airways, Allegiant Airlines, and Avelo Airlines.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] The airport is the fourth largest in New York State.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] Albany International was the first and remains the oldest, municipal airport in the United States.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] In 1908 the airstrip was on a former polo field on Loudonville Road, 3 miles (4.8 km) north of the city in the town of Colonie.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] In 1909 the airport moved to Westerlo Island, in the city of Albany, but at that time was in the town of Bethlehem; the airport was named at this time.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] The airport was named after Teddy Roosevelt's son, Quentin, a fighter pilot during World War I who perished while in air combat.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] A $10,000 prize was established for sustained flight between Albany and New York City; Glenn Curtiss achieved this on May 29, 1910.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] Other early pioneers of aviation that stopped at this early field were Charles Lindbergh, Amelia Earhart, and James Doolittle.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] Mayor John Boyd Thacher II once said "a city without the foresight to build an airport for the new traffic may soon be left behind in the race for competition".
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] He, therefore, decided to build in 1928 a new modern airport on the Shaker site near Albany-Shaker Road in Colonie, not far from the original polo fields used as the first site of the municipal airport.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] The Shakers not only sold the land used but also loaned the use of tractors and tools.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] The early Albany Airport was often closed and threatened with a closure that prompted repeated improvements in the late 1930s and 1940s.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] The airport was closed from January 1939 until December 1940, when it reopened to traffic during daylight hours only, and then with no restrictions since January 1942.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] The airport has not been closed (other than for weather and emergency landings) since.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] The February 1947 C&GS chart shows three 3,500-foot (1,100-meter) runways aimed at 12, 98, and 133 degrees magnetic.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] By 1950, the primary runway was up to 5,000 feet (1,500 meters) in length and was hard-surfaced.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] In the 1980s, the main runway was extended again to the north to 7,200 feet (2,200 m).
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] A few years later, another 1,300 feet (400 m) of the runway was added to the north end of the main runway to bring it to its 8,500 foot (2,600 m) length.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] The north–south runway gained runway centerline lighting and the north-facing runway added touchdown zone lighting to lower landing minimums – including a category two instrument landing system approach.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] ALB was jointly owned and managed by the city and county of Albany until 1960 when Mayor Erastus Corning 2nd ended the city's stake.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] A landside building had ticket counters, a coffee shop, and baggage claim on the first floor and a restaurant, offices and viewing area on the second floor.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] A single-story boarding concourse extended outwards from this building.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] In 1968 this concourse was widened to allow more concessions and boarding space.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] The terminal was expanded again in 1979, with the addition of a new two-story building attached diagonally to the northwest.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] It had boarding gates for Allegheny Airlines on the second floor and baggage carousels on the first floor.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] The Albany County Airport Authority was created by the county in 1993 with a 40-year lease to operate the airport in 1996.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] Construction of a new terminal began on May 16, 1996; it opened in June 1998.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] It was designed by Reynolds, Smith & Hills and Stracher-Roth-Gilmore, and it was built around the existing terminal, most of which was demolished upon its completion.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] Only the 1979 extension remains from the old terminal building.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] In 1999 the Airport Authority began building a 16,000-square-foot (1,500 m2) addition to the new terminal for Southwest Airlines' use.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] The project was completed in 2000 and included the addition of two new dual jet bridges allowing passengers to board and deplane from front and rear doors of the aircraft.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] Construction started in 2019 for various airport improvements.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] This includes a new 1,000 car parking garage, which will open in March 2020; new solar panels, escalators, energy efficient taxiway lighting, concessions are also being installed.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] In addition, some passenger jet bridges are being replaced.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] Frontier Airlines permanently left ALB in late 2022 due to their own budget cuts, leaving several areas with no tenants, however in 2025, Breeze Airways is replacing Frontier.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] In September 2022, the upgrades were finished and the airport secured a large amount of funding to begin a new project.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] This project would extend the bridge that goes from the north garage to the main terminal, adding a new feel to walking through or driving under it.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] It will make space for concessions and retail to appear in those spaces.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] The project will also improve passenger flow for the airport, and will improve the inside of the airport overall.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] The project broke ground in December 2023, and is expected to be completed in mid-2025.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] Between 1946 and 1961, American Airlines, TWA and Colonial/Eastern flew to Albany, but nonstop flights did not travel farther than New York City and Buffalo until 1967.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] Eastern left in 1961 and TWA left in 1965, leaving Mohawk and a few American flights.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] The first jets were American and Mohawk British Aircraft Corporation BAC One-Elevens in late 1966; concurrently, runway 1/19 was extended south sometime in 1966–67, from 5,000–6,000 feet (1,500–1,800 m).
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] Before airline deregulation in 1978, most flights at Albany were on "trunk carriers" (American Airlines and Eastern Air Lines) and "local service carrier" (Allegheny Airlines, which renamed itself USAir in 1979).
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] After deregulation, many new airlines expanded to Albany.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] During 1986–1987, the airline industry saw a series of mergers; after 1989, the US airline industry was dominated by six "legacy carriers": American, United, Delta, Northwest, USAir, and Continental.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] All six served Albany themselves or by their regional affiliates.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] During the 1990s, Albany and other Upstate markets enjoyed little low-fare service, and the legacy carriers mostly kept fares high.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] Southwest Airlines' entry into Albany in 2000 brought a new era of low fare service.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] In early 2001, CommutAir (now CommuteAir) started to invest in an Albany hub.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] The hub was to connect a number of smaller cities in the Northeastern United States via the Albany hub.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] This allowed passengers to travel between cities that lack the demand for a direct flight between them while still bypassing busy, delay-prone hubs in major cities.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] These flights were operated under the Continental Connection brand using Beechcraft 1900Ds.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] The flights were scheduled in banks so that passengers would only have a 20-minute layover in Albany between flights, thereby minimizing travel times.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] At its peak, CommutAir served Allentown, Bangor, Binghamton, Boston, Buffalo, Burlington, Elmira, Portland, Harrisburg, Nantucket, Wilkes-Barre, LaGuardia, Islip, Hartford, White Plains, Manchester, Providence, Syracuse, Rochester, Saranac Lake, Plattsburgh, Montréal, Ottawa.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] The hub was closed down in late 2005 to shift operations to Cleveland.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] As of December 2023, CommuteAir operates several daily flights from Albany to its hub at Dulles International Airport for United Express.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] CommuteAir also has one of its key maintenance bases at Albany, serving its ERJ-145 fleet.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] Previously CommuteAir's main maintenance base was located at Cleveland Hopkins International Airport, but CommuteAir moved the maintenance base to Albany in 2014.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] The main terminal is divided into two levels.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] Level 1 includes the main check-in area, baggage claim, car rental, and taxi services.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] The security checkpoint leads passengers to a central atrium and all three concourses.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] The concourse currently hosts Allegiant Air and United.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] Concourse B hosts American, Delta, and JetBlue.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] Concourse C was opened in June 1998 as part of the airport's $184 million renovation project.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] Concourse C has three gates, with two currently being used by Southwest, while the other is currently assigned to Breeze Airways after being vacated by Frontier.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] Albany International Airport has direct access to I-87 and New York State Route 7 via Albany-Shaker Road, a 3.3-mile (5.3 km), four-lane boulevard.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] On August 14, 2018, New York state officials announced the new I-87 Exit 3 which will provide direct access to Albany International Airport.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] The airport is served by major car rental companies Hertz, Enterprise, Budget, and National as well as by Uber, Lyft, local taxi and limousine services.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] Albany International Airport is served by CDTA Routes 117, 155, and 737.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] Route 737 provides access to Downtown Albany, while Route 117 provides access to Colonie and Guilderland via Colonie Center and Crossgates Mall.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] Adirondack Trailways and Vermont Translines also provides intercity bus service to and from the airport.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] You can also pick up a Vermont Translines bus to Vermont and Southern New York.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] The closest rail station to Albany Airport is Schenectady Amtrak Station in Downtown Schenectady at 10 miles (16 km) from the airport and mainly services western New York and goes east–west.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] For more rail options, Albany–Rensselaer Amtrak Station is 14 miles (23 km) away and services as the main Amtrak operations center in the Capital Region, they service New York City and Western New York, east–west and north–south.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] As of October 2020, a new sidewalk spans across Albany Shaker Road from Route 155 to Wolf Road.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] A pedestrian and bicycle path is also accessible via the new sidewalk at the corner of Albany Shaker Road and Route 155.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] There is also a small viewing area and park at the corner of Albany Shaker road and the exit 3 ramp off I-87.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] On September 16, 1953, American Airlines Flight 723, a Convair 240, was flying Boston-Springfield-Albany-Syracuse-Rochester-Buffalo-Detroit-Chicago when it crashed and caught fire after flying into a series of radio towers in a fog while descending for landing.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] All 28 occupants on board (25 passengers and three crew) were killed.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] On March 3, 1972, Mohawk Airlines Flight 405, a Fairchild Hiller FH-227, crashed into a house in Albany, on approach to Albany County Airport.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] The crew had difficulty getting the cruise lock to disengage in one of the engines.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] While the crew attempted to deal with the problem, the aircraft crashed short of the airfield, killing 16 of the 48 people in the aircraft and one person on the ground.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] On June 17, 2024, at approximately 8:15 A.M., a Piper PA-31 Navajo carrying one pilot took off from Runway 19 at the Albany International Airport only to crash minutes later next to neighborhood and library property in Colonie, killing the pilot.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] The plane was headed to Montreal, where the pilot had been returning after a previous landing in Fayetteville, North Carolina.
[src:exit-sign/albany-international-airport] Two members from the Federal Aviation Administration arrived to the scene of the crash along with several police vehicles and EMTs, with members from The National Transportation Safety Board travelling to Albany from Washington, D.C. to investigate.
[src:exit-sign/area-of-refuge] An **area of refuge** or **safe room** is a place in a building designed to hold occupants during a fire or other emergency when evacuation may not be safe or possible.
[src:exit-sign/area-of-refuge] Occupants can wait there until rescued or relieved by firefighters.
[src:exit-sign/area-of-refuge] In some instances, an area of refuge or refuge area may refer to a designated space in a multi-unit residential building that can provide relief from unsafe or uncomfortable conditions in individual units.
[src:exit-sign/area-of-refuge] An area of refuge is typically supplied with a steady supply of fresh or filtered outside air.
[src:exit-sign/area-of-refuge] A two way communication system is provided on each floor above or below the main floor.
[src:exit-sign/area-of-refuge] A call box is required in each area of refuge, which can call into a central location called a base station.
[src:exit-sign/area-of-refuge] If the station is not attended 24 hours a day, the call must automatically call to an outside location and have two-way voice person to person communication capabilities.
[src:exit-sign/area-of-refuge] Such locations are usually required to be bounded by fire-resistant walls and floors.
[src:exit-sign/area-of-refuge] In the context of climate change, where older buildings may not be designed for changing climate conditions, refuge spaces are sometimes discussed in terms of providing communal areas in multi-unit buildings for when temperature and air quality is not safe or comfortable in individual units.
[src:exit-sign/arthur-b-guise-medal] Guise Medal** was established in 1983 and has been awarded annually starting in 1985 by the Society of Fire Protection Engineers.
[src:exit-sign/arthur-b-guise-medal] Named in memory of Arthur Guise, an engineer who developed dry chemicals as fire extinguishing agents, it recognizes eminent achievement in the advancement of the science and technology of fire protection engineering.
[src:exit-sign/aspirating-smoke-detector] An **aspirating smoke detector** (**ASD**) is a system used in active fire protection, consisting of a central detection unit which draws air through a network of pipes to detect smoke.
[src:exit-sign/aspirating-smoke-detector] The sampling chamber is based on a nephelometer that detects the presence of smoke particles suspended in air by detecting the light scattered by them in the chamber.
[src:exit-sign/aspirating-smoke-detector] ASDs can typically detect smoke before it is visible to the naked eye.
[src:exit-sign/aspirating-smoke-detector] In most cases aspirating smoke detectors require a fan unit to draw in a sample of air from the protected area through its network of pipes.
[src:exit-sign/aspirating-smoke-detector] In 1970 the Australian Commonwealth Scientific and Industrial Research Organisation (CSIRO) used a nephelometer to carry out research into forest fires.
[src:exit-sign/aspirating-smoke-detector] Subsequently, the Australian Postmaster-General's Department engaged the CSIRO to investigate technologies that could prevent service interruption due to fire.
[src:exit-sign/aspirating-smoke-detector] After selecting a sample site to carry out research, the CSIRO suggested that the nephelometer should be used as the benchmark for the APO fire tests.
[src:exit-sign/aspirating-smoke-detector] This was installed to monitor smoke levels within the return-air ducts of the mechanical ventilation system, utilising a chart-recorder output display.
[src:exit-sign/aspirating-smoke-detector] At the conclusion of several weeks of testing, it was discovered that there no commercially available fire detection technology suitable for preventing damage to telephone equipment.
[src:exit-sign/aspirating-smoke-detector] One technology that did show great promise however was the nephelometer itself.
[src:exit-sign/aspirating-smoke-detector] In 1979, Xtralis, then IEI Pty Ltd., produced and sold an air sampling device they called VESDA (Very Early Smoke Detection Apparatus).
[src:exit-sign/aspirating-smoke-detector] The company redesigned the detector in 1982 to provide the reliability, features, size and reduced cost for export markets.
[src:exit-sign/aspirating-smoke-detector] ASD systems have gained popularity due to their ability to sense smoke long before a catastrophic incident.
[src:exit-sign/aspirating-smoke-detector] ASD design corrects shortcomings of conventional smoke detectors by using a sampling pipe with multiple holes.
[src:exit-sign/aspirating-smoke-detector] The air samples are captured and filtered, removing any contaminants or dust to avoid false alarms and then processed by a centralized, highly sensitive laser detection unit.
[src:exit-sign/aspirating-smoke-detector] If smoke is detected, the systems alarm is triggered, and signals are then processed through centralized monitoring stations within a few seconds.
[src:exit-sign/aspirating-smoke-detector] Unlike passive smoke detection systems, including spot detectors, ASD systems actively draw smoke to the detector through bore holes within a piping system that runs throughout the protected area.
[src:exit-sign/aspirating-smoke-detector] Furthermore, ASD systems incorporate integrity monitoring to ensure an alert is raised at any time the ASD's ability to detect smoke is compromised.
[src:exit-sign/aspirating-smoke-detector] This is not the case with passive devices that are generally only electrically monitored with no ability to determine if smoke can actually reach the detection element.
[src:exit-sign/aspirating-smoke-detector] ASD systems incorporate more than one level of alarm.
[src:exit-sign/aspirating-smoke-detector] This allows an ASD system to provide very early warning of an event, prompting investigation at the earliest smouldering stage of a fire when it is easily addressed.
[src:exit-sign/aspirating-smoke-detector] Other alarm levels may be configured to provide fire alarm inputs to fire systems as well as releasing suppression systems.
[src:exit-sign/aspirating-smoke-detector] ASD alarm sensitivities are configurable and can be programmed to levels ranging from thousands of times more sensitive than a conventional detector, to much less sensitive.
[src:exit-sign/aspirating-smoke-detector] The detectors work best in non-volatile environments.
[src:exit-sign/aspirating-smoke-detector] They can also be used in computer cabinets to alert users to the overheating of computer cables or individual computer components.
[src:exit-sign/aspirating-smoke-detector] ASDs are suitable for environments where a highly sensitive rapid smoke detection capability is required.
[src:exit-sign/aspirating-smoke-detector] This makes them suitable in clean rooms; areas which contain goods easily damaged by fire, such as tobacco, electronic rooms and highly flammable liquid and gases.
[src:exit-sign/aspirating-smoke-detector] Often, normal point detectors will recognise the danger too late, as smoke often does not reach the ceiling quickly enough for a fire to be detected in a timely fashion.
[src:exit-sign/aspirating-smoke-detector] As they can be easily hidden, pipe networks are suitable in environments where point detectors can be considered aesthetically displeasing, such as offices, apartments and hotel rooms.
[src:exit-sign/aspirating-smoke-detector] This factor also makes them suitable in locations where point detectors can be easily tampered with, such as in correctional facilities.
[src:exit-sign/aspirating-smoke-detector] Despite their high sensitivity ASDs can be used in dusty or dirty environments as long as correct design, installation and maintenance processes are followed.
[src:exit-sign/aspirating-smoke-detector] Most ASD products can accommodate a broad range of environments and applications – from both confined and open spaces to the cleanest or dirtiest environment, including telecomm, control rooms, waste treatment, mining and more.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] The red or green EXIT sign is more common in North America, especially in the United States.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] A red version was previously used in Canada, but this has been replaced by the ISO standard 'running man' sign.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] An **exit sign** is a pictogram or short text in a public facility (such as a building, aircraft, or boat) marking the location of the closest emergency exit to be used in an emergency that necessitates rapid evacuation.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] Most fire, building, health, and safety codes require exit signs that are always lit.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] Exit signs are intended to be unmistakable and understandable by anyone who can see.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] In the past, this generally meant exit signs that show the word "EXIT" or the equivalent in the local language; increasingly, exit signs around the world are now pictograms, often without supplementary text.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] Early exit signs generally either were made of metal and lit by a nearby incandescent light bulb or were a white glass cover with "EXIT" written in red, placed directly in front of a single-bulb light fixture.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] A flaw in these designs was that in a fire the power to the light often failed.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] In addition, the fixtures, despite their brightness, could be hard to see through smoke.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] The biggest problem was that the exit sign was hardly distinguishable from an ordinary safety lighting fixture commonly installed above doors in the past.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] The problem was partially solved by using red-tinted bulbs instead.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] Better signs were soon developed that more resembled today's modern exit sign, with an incandescent bulb in a rectangular box that backlit the word "EXIT" on one or both sides.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] Larger than its predecessors, this version of the exit sign was easier to see.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] The sign was still only useful as long as mains power remained on.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] As battery-backup systems became smaller and more efficient, some exit signs began to use a dual-power system.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] Under normal conditions, the exit sign was lit by mains power and the battery was maintained in a charged state.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] In the event of a power outage, the battery would supply power to light the sign.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] Early battery-backup systems were big, heavy, and costly.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] Modern systems are lightweight, can be installed virtually anywhere, and are integrated into the fixture, rather than requiring a separate box.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] As batteries improved, so did the amount of time that a fixture could remain lit on batteries.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] While exit signs were more visible due to large letters, even a 60-watt incandescent bulb shining through a plastic or glass cover could appear somewhat dim under certain conditions.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] Incandescent bulbs are still in use because they are cheap and common, even though they use more electricity and require more or less frequent replacement.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] Incandescent bulbs lit 24/7 have a greatly extended lifespan compared to ones that cycle on and off.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] When used in exit signs, they are often operated at a lower voltage than rated, which further extends their lifetime, at the trade-off of reduced light output and greatly reduced energy efficiency.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] With the development of fluorescent lamp and light-emitting diode technology, exit signs could be made even brighter to compensate for the limited visibility in a fire situation, while using less electricity.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] Fluorescent lamps are used in the same way as incandescent bulbs, back-lighting both sides of an exit fixture from within.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] LED signs combine a large number of bright light-emitting diodes to illuminate the sign from inside.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] An exit sign is constantly lit; fluorescent bulbs need to be changed more often than LEDs, although the absence of frequent on/off cycles extends the life of fluorescent lamps significantly.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] Generally, LEDs have a very long life, and may last for 10 years or more of continuous use, although their brightness may gradually diminish.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] Radio-luminescent and phosphorescent signs that require no electricity have also been developed, and have been used since the 1970s.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] Radio-luminescence uses the radioactive decay of tritium gas to illuminate the sign, while phosphorescence uses light-emitting pigments to glow in the dark.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] While both of these types of signs meet California State Fire Marshal standards, electricity is used in the vast majority of signs.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] Most exit signs in the world use pictograms.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] Sometimes paired with a combination of text to indicate the direction of emergency exits.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] However, countries such as the United States and Philippines refuse to strictly enforce it at all.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] Though, former adopters of text based EXIT signs such as Canada, Singapore, and Hong Kong have changed their safety codes to encourage the use of pictograms.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] The Philippines, a country which lacks a uniform standard, uses pictograms; signs reading "EXIT", "FIRE EXIT", or "EMERGENCY EXIT"; and combinations of pictograms and text.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] In the United States, the International Building Code, and in some jurisdictions, National Fire Protection Association (NFPA) 101 Life Safety Code, generally define the standard for exit signs.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] The IBC, starting with the 2021 edition, allows pictograms for internally illuminated exit signs.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] NFPA 101 - 7.10.3.1 requires textual exit signs for all standard mounted applications; pictograms are allowed instead of or in addition to text if approved by local authorities and compliant with NFPA 170.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] The NFPA has also approved the ISO pictogram as an option for low-level glow-in-the-dark signs.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] New York City local law 26 requires these low-level pictograms in all high-rise buildings.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] In tunnels, the Transportation Research Board recommends the ISO symbol.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] Newer Airbus, Bombardier CS100, and Boeing 787 Dreamliner planes use the new pictogram exit signs, which were approved by the FAA in 2012 and 2014 (depending on aircraft type).
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] The renovated Government Center subway station in Boston, and the MBTA's newer Type 9 streetcars for the Green Line and new Orange Line and Red Line trains made by CRRC, use signs bearing "EXIT" in white on a green background beside the ISO pictogram.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] Recent terminal renovations at the Albany International Airport have added supplemental ISO pictogram exit signs on terminal way-finding signs near the emergency exits.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] Parts of the Corning Museum of Glass use an exclusive variant of the ISO pictogram, pointing to exits, along with textual signs.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] The Cherokee Nation's Durbin Feeling Language Center uses the ISO pictogram instead of text.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] Modern exit signs often can be seen indicating the path to an exit in commercial and large residential buildings that comply with fire code.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] In most situations, the owner of the building is responsible for complying with exit-sign requirements.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] This is especially true in older buildings that serve as multiple residences, such as apartment buildings, hotels, and campus dormitories.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] Modern fixtures are usually in a rugged plastic or metal housing securely bolted to the wall or ceiling.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] The signs have the word "EXIT", or a picture representing exit, on both sides.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] Single-sided signs are also available for wall-mount installations.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] The signs often have metal or plastic knock-outs which can optionally be removed so that an arrow is also lit pointing left or right.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] Modern exit signs are often combined with other safety devices, such as emergency floodlighting for supplementary area illumination.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] Modern exit signs are also, to some degree, flame retardant.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] Exit signs draw a relatively small amount of power, and can generally be added onto any existing electrical circuit without adverse effects.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] In addition, specialized LED lamps with "candelabra" sized screw-in bases are available to replace the always-on incandescent lamps in older exit signs.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] This allows the existing fixtures to be easily upgraded to save energy, without the expense of complete replacement.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] Most recently, Photoluminescent, Hybrid Photoluminescent and LEC (light emitting capacitor) exit signs have come to market.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] Photoluminescent signs consume no power and have an operational life of 30+ years.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] Hybrid Photoluminescent Exit Signs consume as little as 0.74 W of power.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] LEC signs are also called electroluminescent (EL), only consuming 1/4 W of power, and have an operational life of 30+ years which far exceeds the typical 10-year life of an LED sign.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] It is often a serious offence for a building owner or landlord to not comply with the fire/building code in terms of Exit signage.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] In July 2016, for example, a fire in a Toronto apartment caused the death of one person and injured many others.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] An investigation found that Emergency lights and Exit signs were not properly illuminated, and the landlord was fined $21,000 for "not properly illuminating exit signs and having no record of emergency lighting tests", and another $50,000 for other infractions to the code relating to fire doors.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] In most regions, including China, the European Union, Japan, and South Korea exit signs have green lettering.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] (In this color scheme, red is reserved to indicate prohibited activities.) In Australia, Canada, New Zealand, and most European countries, pictograms are used in place of the word "exit".
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] European sign directive 92/58/EEC of 24 June 1992 indicates that the signs should be green in color to indicate a safe place of exit.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] BS EN 1838:1999 and BS 5266-7:1999 also govern emergency lighting applications.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] In the United States, exit signs can be red or green, but traditionally they have been red.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] Many states or cities have enacted building codes that specify the sign color.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] For example, in Baltimore, Salt Lake City, and Portland, Oregon, green is required.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] New York City, Rhode Island, and Chicago (along with the rest of Illinois) require that exit signs be red.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] New and renovated buildings in Canada are required to use the international standard green "running man" pictogram.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] The 1995 Canadian national building code required "red letters on a contrasting background or white letters on a red background ... spelling EXIT or SORTIE"; however, the 2010 Code calls for a switch from the red EXIT signs to the green "running-man" signs.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] The national building code informs provincial and municipal building codes but does not have legal status itself.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] Most Canadian jurisdictions require the international green "running-man" pictogram; however, some have allowed red "EXIT" signs to be maintained in older properties so long as one style is used consistently throughout the building.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] Green fluorescent signs can be seen better in dark conditions than other colours, as the human rod cell is more sensitive to these wavelengths.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] Newly installed exit signs in Australia and New Zealand are green with a white "running man" ISO 7010 figure.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] Previously, green-written 'EXIT' signs were standard.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] There is a trend towards providing a more accessible, socially inclusive exit sign design based on universal design principles, including consideration for people with disabilities in the overall exit sign strategy for a building or facility.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] The Accessible Exit Sign Project, which started in Australia in 2014 and has spread to New Zealand and the United States, is an international awareness campaign that promotes the need for an accessible means of egress.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] Advocates propose that appropriate exit signage to identify the accessible means of egress is a critical component to successful emergency planning for any building.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] The proposed new exit sign design features an "Accessible Means of Egress Icon", which includes an adaptation of the "running man" symbol with a new wheelchair symbol.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] The design is considered an enhanced version of the ISO 7010 and ISO 21542 accessible exit sign that shows the "running man" and International Symbol of Access at the end of the sign.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] The universally inclusive design with the "running man" and "Accessible Means of Egress Icon" wheelchair symbol essentially share the same upper torso, and the design shows the two moving through the door together.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] The Global Alliance on Accessible Technologies and Environments (GAATES) has stated that the introduction of the "Accessible Means of Egress Icon" onto exit signage changes the current discriminatory approach to emergency exit signs and presents a fully inclusive design.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] "The combined ‘Running Man’ and ‘Accessible Means of Egress Icon’ […] are working together to escape the building.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] They move in unison, display the same urgency and motion and appear to be travelling at the same speed.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] Their heads are forward, showing their haste.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] The accessible exit signs are now being produced in Australia, New Zealand, United States, and United Kingdom, also featuring braille and tactile lettering suitable for people that have low vision or are blind.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] The design is intended to show where wheelchair accessible exit routes, evacuation lifts, evacuation devices and areas of refuge are located.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] The concept also provides more intuitive building design to assist people that are blind or have low vision to locate an exit.
[src:exit-sign/exit-sign] The design also meets the intent of the UN Convention on the Rights of Persons with Disabilities which requires signatory countries to consider the need for universal design in buildings.
